\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Measuring agreement using guessing models and knowledge coefficients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Jonas Moss 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
orcid{0000-0002-6876-6964}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Department of Data Science and Analytics
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

BI Norwegian Business School
\emph on

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

jonas.moss@bi.no
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Several measures of agreement, such as the Perreault–Leigh coefficient,
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

, and the recent coefficient of van Oest, are based on explicit models of
 how judges make their ratings.
 To handle such measures of agreement under a common umbrella, we propose
 a class of models called guessing models, which contains most models of
 how judges make their ratings.
 Every guessing model have an associated measure of agreement we call the
 knowledge coefficient.
 Under certain assumptions on the guessing models, the knowledge coefficient
 will be equal to the multi-rater Cohen's kappa, Fleiss' kappa, the Brennan–Pred
iger coefficient, or other less-established measures of agreement.
 We provide several sample estimators of the knowledge coefficient, valid
 under varying assumptions, and their asymptotic distributions.
 After a sensitivity analysis and a simulation study of confidence intervals,
 we find that the Brennan–Prediger coefficient typically outperforms the
 others, with much better coverage under unfavorable circumstances.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Introduction"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most popular measures of agreement are chance-corrected.
 These can usually be written on the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p_{a}-p_{ca}}{1-p_{ca}},\label{eq:chance-corrected measure of agrement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the percent agreement and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ca}$
\end_inset

 is a notion of chance agreement.
 The best known coefficients in this class are the (weighted) Cohen's kappa
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Cohen1960-mp,Cohen1968-sb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Krippendorff's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Krippendorff1970-gl"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 alpha, Scott's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Scott1955-vn"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 pi, and Fleiss' 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Fleiss1971-to"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 kappa.
 The difference between these measures lies solely in their definition of
 the chance agreement, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ca}$
\end_inset

.
 These coefficient make few to no assumptions about the underlying distribution
 of ratings, and can be regarded as non-parametric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is also possible to model the judgment process directly, and then attempt
 to derive reasonable chance-corrected measures of agreement from these
 models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Janes1979-ih"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Examples of measures of agreements developed in this way include the Perreault–
Leigh coefficient 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Perreault1989-mg"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Maxwell's RE coefficient 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Maxwell1977-lf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Aickin's 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Aickin1990-nj"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the estimators of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Klauer1996-jd"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and the more recent coefficient of van Oest 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Van_Oest2019-pm,Van_Oest2021-jt"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These measures of agreement depend on the parameters of the underlying
 judgment process, and may be considered semi-parametric instead of non-parametr
ic.
 The models used by the above-mentioned authors may be called 
\emph on
guessing models
\emph default
, as they represent ratings as being either known or guessed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make it clear what these models are about, consider the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

textbook case argument
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Grove1981-wb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Chapter 4, for an extended justification"
before "see"
key "Gwet2014-iu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 When two judges classify people into, say, psychiatric categories, some
 people are bound to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

textbook cases
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, i.e., being classifiable without much effort.
 Disagreement between competent judges will mostly occur when subjects are
 hard to classify, when the judges have to guess.
 But judges may agree on hard subjects as well, simply due to chance.
 We can then define a coefficient of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agreement due to knowledge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as the proportion of textbook cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The guessing model, introduced in the next section, will encompass the textbook
 case model and many more.
 As we will show, it is a generalization of several judgment process models
 discussed in the literature on measures of agreement.
 Any guessing model is associated with a 
\emph on
knowledge coefficient, 
\emph default
a measure of agreement defined directly from its parameters.
 These coefficients generalize the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agreement due to knowledge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from Grove's textbook case to more general settings.
 The knowledge coefficient can, under various additional assumptions, be
 easily estimated from the data; the details are in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:main theorem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In some cases, it equals already established coefficients such as the Brennan–P
rediger coefficient 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Brennan1981-kf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or Fleiss' kappa, but we will establish some less familiar formulas as
 well.
 We provide methods for doing inference for our proposed coefficients, based
 on the delta rule and the theory of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics.
 Using sensitivity analyses and confidence interval simulations, we find
 that the Brennan–Prediger coefficient generally outperforms its competitors
 as an estimator of the knowledge coefficient, with reasonably small bias
 and variance in a variety of circumstances.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Guessing models
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Guessing-models"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We work in the setting where one rating is definitely true, such as psychiatric
 diagnoses.
 Thus we exclude problems such as measuring agreement between movie reviewers,
 where there is no true rating.
 We also exclude measures of agreement between continuous measurement instrument
, as continuous ratings are rarely exactly right.
 For instance, an instrument for measuring blood glucose may be decidedly
 better than another, but will never be precisely on the spot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will consider only agreement studies with a rectangular design, i.e., when
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 judges rate 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 items into one of 
\begin_inset Formula $C<\infty$
\end_inset

 categories, with every item being rated exactly once by every judge.
 Moreover, we will understand the set of judges as fixed and the set of
 items as being random and increasing with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 These assumptions may not be necessary for all of the results in this paper,
 but will make the presentation easier to follow, and are necessary for
 the asymptotic results.
 Denote the probability that the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 judges will rate an item as belonging to the categories 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots x_{R})$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The joint distribution of the 
\emph on
guessing model
\emph default
 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x\mid s,x^{\star})=\prod_{r=1}^{R}\left[s_{r}1[x_{r}=x^{\star}]+(1-s_{r})q_{r}(x_{r})\right].\label{eq:full guessing model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $x_{r}$
\end_inset

 is the rating given by the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

th judge on an item.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $s=\{s_{1},s_{2},\ldots,s_{r}\}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\emph on
skill-difficulty parameters
\emph default
, the probabilities that the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

th judge knows the correct classification of an item.
 The skill-difficulty parameters can be deterministic or random.
 For instance, they can be sampled from a Beta distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is the true classification the item, an unknown latent variable.
 These are assumed to be independent of the skill-difficulty parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 The distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x^{\star})$
\end_inset

, the 
\emph on
true rating distribution
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $q_{r}(x)$
\end_inset

 are the 
\emph on
guessing distributions
\emph default
, the distributions the ratings are drawn from when the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

th judge does not know the true classification of the item.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may use 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x^{\star})$
\end_inset

 to remove the dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 from the univariate guessing model, giving
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x_{r}\mid s)=s_{r}t(x_{r})+(1-s_{r})q_{r}(x_{r}).\label{eq:univariate guessing model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x_{r}\mid s)$
\end_inset

 is straight-forward.
 When faced with an item, a judge 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 knows its true classification, drawn from 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x)$
\end_inset

, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{r}$
\end_inset

.
 If the judge doesn't know the true classification, the rating will be drawn
 at random from his potentially idiosyncratic guessing distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{r}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 We do not allow for guessing distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{r}$
\end_inset

 that depend both on both the true classification 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

 and the judge, as it would make the parameters unidentifiable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have said nothing about the joint distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $(s_{1},s_{2},\dots,s_{R},x^{\star})$
\end_inset

 except that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is independent of the skill-difficulty parameters.
 This assumption is not realistic in all situations.
 For instance, correctly diagnosing patients with Down syndrome is easier
 than correctly diagnosing patients with ADHD, implying that 
\begin_inset Formula $E[s_{r}\mid x^{\star}=\text{Down syndrome]}$
\end_inset

 dominates 
\begin_inset Formula $E[s_{r}\mid x^{\star}=\text{ADHD]}$
\end_inset

, which violates independence of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 The independence assumption is not needed for the definition of the guessing
 model to make sense, but will be used in the remainder of the paper as
 it is required for Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:main theorem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In most settings with latent parameters one would decide on a model for
 them, such as multivariate normal in the case of linear random effects
 models.
 Instead of following this route, we will impose additional assumptions
 on the skill-difficulty parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, the guessing distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{r}$
\end_inset

, and/or the true distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to make the problem manageable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The guessing model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:full guessing model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 has, to our knowledge, not been presented in this generality before.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Theorem 5 and Section 9"
key "Klauer1996-jd"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 define a model of almost as high generality, but does not allow the the
 skill-difficulty parameters to differ between items.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Knowledge coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have introduced the guessing model in order to define the notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agreement due to knowledge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in a precise way.
 To gain an intuition about what we're getting at, first consider the case
 of two judges with potentially different, but deterministic, skill-difficulty
 parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The probability that two judges agree on the classification of an item
 because they both know its classification is the product of their skill
 parameters, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=s_{1}s_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agree on classification of an item because they both know its classification
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is cumbersome to read, we will call it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

knowledgeable agreement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agree knowledgeably
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from now.
 Extending this notion to 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 judges, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{r_{1}>r_{2}}s_{r_{1}}s_{r_{2}}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that a randomly selected pair of judges will agree knowledge
ably on a pair of ratings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another simple case happens when there are 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 judges with random skill-difficulty parameters that do not wary across
 judges when the item is fixed, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}=S_{2}=\cdots=S_{R}$
\end_inset

, where we use capital letters to emphasize that the 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{r}$
\end_inset

 are random.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $E(S_{r}^{2})$
\end_inset

 is the probability of knowledgeable agreement.
 Finally, in the general guessing model, we find that the probability of
 knowledgeable agreement among two judges is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nu=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{r_{1}>r_{2}}E[S_{r_{1}}S_{r_{2}}].\label{eq:knowledgable agreement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Earlier guessing models
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Earlier-guessing-models"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The guessing model and its associated knowledge coefficient are extensions,
 formalizations, or slight modifications of models or coefficients used
 in several earlier papers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The two models of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Maxwell1977-lf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:maxwell"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Section 3"
key "Maxwell1977-lf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 works in the setting of two judges and binary ratings.
 From his Table II one can derive the the joint model for two ratings 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}$
\end_inset

 by two judges as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x_{1},x_{2})=\alpha p(x_{1})1[x_{1}=x_{2}]+(1-\alpha)p(x_{1})p(x_{2}),\label{eq:maxwell joint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the marginal distribution of the data.
 Maxwell then shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\Cor(X_{1},X_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maxwell's joint distribution is the unconditional variant of a guessing
 model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:full guessing model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with two judges, i.e., a model on the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(x_{1},x_{2}\mid s,x^{\star}) & =\{s_{1}1[x_{1}=x^{\star}]+(1-s_{1})q_{r}(x_{1})\}\{s_{2}1[x_{2}=x^{\star}]+(1-s_{2})q_{r}(x_{2})\}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with associated knowledge coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The guessing model satisfies 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The judges' guessing distributions are equal to the marginal distribution,
 i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}(x)=q_{2}(x)=p(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The true distribution is assumed to be equal to the marginal distribution,
 i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x)=p(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Both judges share the same skill-difficulty parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 It is Bernoulli distributed with success probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=P(s=1)=Es^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 will 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 if the the case is easy to judge (i.e., a textbook case) and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 otherwise, and the probability of an item being a textbook case is 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Section 4, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Maxwell1977-lf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is still working with binary data and two judges.
 He describes a guessing model where (iii) above still holds, but (i) and
 (ii) are replaced with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Both the judges' guessing distributions are uniform, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}(x)=q_{2}(x)=1/2$
\end_inset

 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The true distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x)$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then he derives the knowledge for this model, the Maxwell RE (abbreviation
 of 
\emph on
random error
\emph default
) coefficient for binary data, a special case of the Brennan–Prediger coefficien
t, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nu_{BP}=\frac{p_{a}-1/C}{1-1/C},\label{eq:Brennan-Prediger coefficient}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, in this case equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, is the number of categories.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Perreault–Leigh coefficient (1989)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Perreault1989-mg"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 devise an explicit model for the rating procedure involving two judges
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C<\infty$
\end_inset

 categories.
 Using an index for reliability 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, they define the univariate model
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x)=st(x)+(1-s)C^{-1}.\label{eq:Perreault--Leigh model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The model is similar to the second Maxwell model, except that the skill-difficul
ty parameters are deterministic and constant across judges and the number
 of categories is arbitrary.
 The guessing distributions are uniform, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{2}=1/C$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x)$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary.
 From this model they derive that 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\sqrt{(p_{a}-1/C)/(1-1/C)}=\sqrt{\nu_{BP}}$
\end_inset

, the square root of the Brennan–Prediger coefficient.
 Hence the knowledge coefficient is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=s^{2}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Aickin's coefficient (1990)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Aickin1990-nj"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 works in a setting of two judges.
 He defines the joint model for two ratings 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}$
\end_inset

 by two judges as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x_{1},x_{2})=(1-\alpha)q_{1}(x_{1})q_{2}(x_{2})+\alpha1[x_{1}=x_{2}]\frac{q_{1}(x_{1})q_{2}(x_{1})}{\sum_{x=1}^{C}q_{1}(x_{1})q_{2}(x_{1})},\label{eq:Aickin model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the goal of doing inference on 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 He does this using maximum likelihood, estimating the distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 alongside 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aickin's model is a guessing model and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\nu$
\end_inset

 is its knowledge coefficient.
 The assumptions of the guessing model are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
As in the first Maxwell model, both judges share the same skill-difficulty
 parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 It is Bernoulli distributed with success probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=P(s=1)=Es^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The judges' guessing distributions are arbitrary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The true distribution is assumed to be equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x)=q_{1}(x)q_{2}(x)/\sum_{x=1}^{C}q_{1}(x)q_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That Aicken's model is a guessing model satisfying conditions (i)–(iii)
 is a direct consequence of the following fact.
 Whenever the number of judges is two and the skill-difficulty parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $s\sim\text{Bernoulli}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is the same for both judges, the guessing model has unconditional distribution
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x_{1},x_{2})=\alpha1[x_{1}=x_{2}]t(x_{1})+(1-\alpha)q_{1}(x_{1})q_{2}(x_{2}).\label{eq:generalized aicken model-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The details are in the appendix, p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "subsec:Proof-that-Aickin's"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assumption (iii) is not justified by Aickin, and does not appear to be necessary.
 If we define the generalized Aicken model as the guessing model satisfying
 only (i) and (ii) above, with an arbitrary number of judges 
\begin_inset Formula $R\geq2$
\end_inset

, its parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nu,q_{1},q_{2},...q_{R})$
\end_inset

 are identified when 
\begin_inset Formula $C>2$
\end_inset

.
 This can be shown following the arguments laid out in the proof of Theorem
 1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Klauer1996-jd"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Klauer–Batchelder model (1996)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Klauer1996-jd"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 performs a detailed structural analysis of the guessing model with identical
 skill-difficulty parameters.
 In our notation, their equation 2 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x\mid s,x^{\star})=s1[x=x^{\star}]+(1-s)q_{r}(x),\label{eq:klauer-batcheleder}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the guessing distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1},q_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the true distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary.
 They show that, provided the number of judges is equal to two, then 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "eq. 3"
key "Klauer1996-jd"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x_{1},x_{2})=p(x_{1})p(x_{2})+s^{2}t(x_{1})[1[x_{1}=x_{2}]-t(x_{2})],\label{eq:klauer-batchelder2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which does not depend directly on the guessing distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{r}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:klauer-batchelder2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 provides a nice interpretation of the skill-difficulty parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

: The higher 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is, the more weight will be on the main diagonal of the agreement matrix
 and less on the off-diagonal elements.
 Moreover, in Theorem 5, they extend equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:klauer-batchelder2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to the case of two judges with different deterministic skill-difficulty
 parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They show the model is identified when the 
\begin_inset Formula $C>2$
\end_inset

, and propose to estimate it by maximum likelihood using the EM algorithm
 developed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hu1994-np"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In addition, they show that 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}$
\end_inset

 equals Cohen's kappa when both guessing distributions are equal to the
 true distribution; they also show that 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}$
\end_inset

 equals the Brennan–Prediger coefficient when both distributions are uniform.
 We generalize these results to arbitrary skill-difficulty parameters and
 an arbitrary number of judges in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:main theorem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
van Oest's coefficient (2019)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Modifying the setup of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Perreault1989-mg"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Van_Oest2019-pm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 develops a guessing model for two judges and 
\begin_inset Formula $C<\infty$
\end_inset

 categories.
 He assumes the guessing distributions are equal to the marginal distribution,
 i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}(x)=q_{2}(x)=p(x)$
\end_inset

, and that the skill-difficulty coefficients are deterministic and constant
 across judges.
 The marginal model becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x)=st(x)+(1-s)p(x).\label{eq:van Oest model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Van_Oest2019-pm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proceeds to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 equals the weighted Scott's pi under these circumstances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The knowledge coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x,y)$
\end_inset

 be an
\emph on
 agreement weighting function
\emph default
.
 This is a function of two arguments that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x,y)\leq1$
\end_inset

 and equals 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x,x)=1$
\end_inset

.
 The purpose of this function is to measure the degree of similarity between
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is understood as the maximal degree of similarity.
 While there are infinitely many weighting functions, only three are in
 widespread use.
 The first is the 
\emph on
nominal weight
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w(x_{1},x_{2})=1[x_{1}=x_{2}]=\begin{cases}
1, & x_{1}=x_{2},\\
0, & \textrm{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

With this function, similarity does not come in degrees, but it does with
 the 
\emph on
quadratic weighting function
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x_{1},x_{2})=1-(x_{1}-x_{2})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\emph on
absolute value weighting function
\emph default
 (sometimes called the 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
 weighting function) measures the similarity between 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 using the absolute value, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x_{1},x_{2})=1-|x_{1}-x_{2}|$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{r}(x)$
\end_inset

 is the marginal distribution of ratings for judge 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 be ratings by two different judges 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Define the 
\emph on
weighted agreement
\emph default
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
p_{wa} & = & \binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{r_{1}>r_{2}}\sum_{x_{1},x_{2}}w(x_{1},x_{2})p(x_{r_{1}},x_{r_{2}}),\label{eq:Weighted probability of agreement}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

the 
\emph on
weighted Cohen-type chance agreement
\emph default
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
p_{wc} & = & \binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{r_{1}>r_{2}}\sum_{x_{1},x_{2}}w(x_{1},x_{2})p(x_{r_{1}})p(x_{r_{2}}),\label{eq:Fleiss-type weighted probability of chance agreement}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and the 
\emph on
weighted Fleiss-type chance agreement 
\emph default
as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
p_{wf} & = & R^{-2}\sum_{r_{1},r_{2}}\sum_{x_{1},x_{2}}w(x_{1},x_{2})p(x_{r_{1}})p(x_{r_{2}}).\label{eq:Cohen-type weighted probability of chance agreement}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The difference between the two notions of weighted chance agreement should
 be clear enough.
 The Fleiss-type probability of chance agreement counts the cases when a
 judge agrees with himself, while the Cohen-type does not.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{C}\}$
\end_inset

 be the set of possible ratings and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 an agreement weighting function, define the weighting matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Formula $C\times C$
\end_inset

 matrix with elements 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{ir}=w(x_{i},x_{r})$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{wf}=p^{T}Wp,$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p=R^{-1}\sum_{r}p_{r}$
\end_inset

 is the marginal distribution of ratings, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{wc}=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{r_{1}>r_{2}}p_{r_{1}}^{T}Wp_{r_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is the nominal weight, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{wa},p_{wc}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{wf}$
\end_inset

 are proper probabilities, and are often referred to as unweighted probabilities
 of (chance) agreement.
 We do not require that the weighting functions to be non-negative, hence
 the quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{wa},p_{wc}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{wf}$
\end_inset

 are not, in general, proper probabilities.
 Since the number of categories 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is finite, however, we may assume that the weighting function is positive
 by normalizing, i.e., redefining the weighting function to 
\begin_inset Formula $1-[1-w(x_{1},x_{2})]/\max_{x_{1},x_{2}}(1-w(x_{1},x_{2}))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The knowledge coefficient theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we have seen, well-known coefficients such as Scott's pi and the Brennan–Pred
iger can be understood as knowledge coefficients, albeit under restrictive
 assumptions such as all judges being equally skilled.
 The following theorem describes less stringent sets of assumptions that
 keeps interpretable expressions for the knowledge coefficient.
 We must assume either that all guessing distributions are equal or that
 the skill-difficulty parameters have zero pairwise covariance to get anywhere.
 In addition, we must assume something about either the true distribution
 or the guessing distribution.
 We never have to assume that every judge is equally competent, and we never
 have to assume anything about the number of categories rated, however.
 The content of the theorem, including the required assumptions, is summarized
 in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:coefficients"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

