\begin_layout Standard
From Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:centered on uniform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we see that the Cohen–Brennan–Prediger coefficient performs worst in every
 setting, , usually by a large margin, except when the true distribution
 is uniform.
 Moreover, the Brennan–Prediger coefficient performs well in every scenario.
 The bias 
\begin_inset Formula $|\nu_{BP}-\nu|$
\end_inset

 will be likely be overshadowed by sampling variability for most conceivable
 sample sizes.
 Finally, there is little difference between Cohen's kappa, Fleiss' kappa,
 and the Cohen–Fleiss coefficient.
 Their biases are quite small, at least when the true distribution isn't
 far away from the uniform distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
True distribution centered on the marginal distribution
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:True-distribution-centered-marginal"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To derive Fleiss' kappa, Cohen's kappa, and the Cohen–Fleiss coefficient,
 we assumed that the true distribution equals the marginal distribution.
 We can use an asymmetric Dirichlet distribution to extend this scenario,
 just as we used the symmetric Dirichlet distribution to extend the scenario
 when the true distribution is uniform.
 This time we won't use the uniform distribution as a base true distribution,
 but randomly generated distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, from a symmetric Dirichlet distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=5$
\end_inset

, instead.
 The rest of the settings are identical to the previous sensitivity study.
\end_layout

