\begin_layout Standard
The results are in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:centered on marginal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 We see that the Cohen–Brennan–Prediger coefficient performs worst in every
 setting, usually by a large margin.
 Surprisingly, the Brennan–Prediger coefficient performs best in 
\begin_inset Formula $6/9$
\end_inset

 cases, and its performance is good in the remaining cases too.
 Some of the biases in the table are unacceptably large.
 Only the Brennan–Prediger coefficient has a bias less than 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1$
\end_inset

 in every case.
 Finally, there is little difference between Cohen's kappa, Fleiss' kappa,
 and the Cohen–Fleiss coefficient.
 The Cohen–Fleiss coefficient does better, especially when the true distribution
 equals the marginal distribution, but the difference in performance is
 insignificant under slight deviations from equality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
When 
\begin_inset Formula $E[s_{r_{1}}s_{r_{2}}]\neq E[s_{r_{1}}]E[s_{r_{2}}]$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:dependence"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To model dependent skill-difficulty parameters, let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-variate distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $s\sim F$
\end_inset

.
 Evidently, the only restriction on 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is that it's a multivariate distribution function on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 A natural way to model situation is to use copulas for the dependence structure
 and a density on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 for the marginals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nelsen2007-qj"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We will use the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-variate Gaussian copula with uniform correlation structure, i.e., the correlation
 matrix parameter
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & \rho & \cdots & \rho\\
\rho & 1 & \cdots & \rho\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
\rho & \rho & \cdots & 1
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Denote this Gaussian copula by 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\rho}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{(a,b)}$
\end_inset

 be the cumulative distribution function of a beta distribution with parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, and define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{\rho,a,b}(s_{1},s_{2},\ldots,s_{R})=C_{\rho}(H_{(a,b)}(s_{1}),H_{(a,b)}(s_{2}),\ldots,H_{(a,b)}(s_{R})).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\rho,a,b}$
\end_inset

 is a reasonable model for dependent skill-difficulty parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the small correlation parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=0.2$
\end_inset

.
 The rest of the settings are exactly the same as the previous setting,
 including the beta parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $a=7,b=1/2$
\end_inset

.
 We see that the Cohen–Brennan–Prediger coefficient still outperforms the
 alternatives when the true distribution equals the uniform distribution,
 but only by a an order of magnitude.
 Since the alternatives to the Cohen–Brennan–Prediger coefficient also performs
 well in this situation, with biases likely to be overshadowed by sampling
 error, the case for it remains weak.
 Similarly, we see that the Cohen–Fleiss coefficient still outperforms Cohen's
 kappa and Fleiss' kappa, roughly by one order of magnitude, a much smaller
 margin than before.
 These comments also hold for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=0.5,0.9$
\end_inset

, which can be found in the online appendix (p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "tab:centered on uniform-1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

