\begin_layout Subsection
Recommendations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can draw three tentative conclusions from the sensitivity analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Unless the researcher can make sure the true distribution is exactly uniform,
 the Cohen–Brennan–Prediger coefficient is probably not worth reporting.
 Its bias is often unacceptably large, frequently larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Brennan–Prediger coefficient performs reasonably well in all situations,
 with biases less than 
\begin_inset Formula $0.01$
\end_inset

 when the true distribution is centered on the uniform distribution.
 It performs decently in the second scenario as well, with biases at around
 
\begin_inset Formula $0.05$
\end_inset

 across the board.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Cohen–Fleiss coefficient does slightly better than Cohen's kappa and
 Fleiss' kappa, but not enough to be important.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the Cohen–Fleiss coefficient does slightly better than Fleiss' kappa
 and Cohen's kappa, it appears prudent to report it.
 However, we believe it would be best not to.
 For both Fleiss' kappa and Cohen's kappa are well-known chance-corrected
 measures of agreement.
 In contrast, the Cohen–Fleiss coefficient is neither well-known nor a chance-co
rrected measure of agreement.
 We recommend that you report Cohen's kappa (or Fleiss' kappa) together
 with the Brennan–Prediger coefficient.
 This solution accounts both for the scenario when the marginal distribution
 is close to the true distribution and the scenario when the uniform distributio
n is close to the marginal distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Inference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The asymptotic distribution of the coefficients Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:coefficients"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can readily be calculated using the theory of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following Lemma is instrumental in constructing the confidence intervals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
Define the parameter vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}=(p_{wa},p_{wc},p_{wf})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{p}}=(\hat{p}_{wa},\hat{p}_{wc},\hat{p}_{wf})$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 be the covariance matrix with elements 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{6}
\sigma_{11} & = & \sigma_{A}^{2} & = & \Var\mu_{wa}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}) & ,\quad & \sigma_{12} & = & \sigma_{AC}^{2} & = & 2\Cov\left(\mu_{wa}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}),\mu_{wc}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})\right),\\
\sigma_{22} & = & \sigma_{C}^{2} & = & 4\Var\mu_{wc}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}) & ,\quad & \sigma_{13} & = & \sigma_{AF}^{2} & = & 2\Cov\left(\mu_{wa}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}),\mu_{wc}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})\right),\\
\sigma_{33} & = & \sigma_{F}^{2} & = & 4\Var\mu_{wf}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}) & ,\quad & \sigma_{23} & = & \sigma_{CF}^{2} & = & 4\Cov\left(\mu_{wc}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}),\mu_{wf}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})\right).
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{n}(\hat{\boldsymbol{p}}-\boldsymbol{p})\stackrel{d}{\to}N(0,\Sigma).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
See Lemma 1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Anon2022-ep"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{wa}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}),\mu_{wc}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{wf}(\boldsymbol{X}_{1})$
\end_inset

 can be found there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An application of the delta method yields the following.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:The-asymptotic-variances"

\end_inset

The coefficients in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:coefficients"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are asymptotically normal, and their asymptotic variances are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sigma_{F}^{2} & = & \sigma_{A}^{2}\frac{1}{(1-p_{wf})^{2}}-2\sigma_{FA}\frac{1-p_{wa}}{(1-p_{wf})^{3}}+\sigma_{F}^{2}\frac{(1-p_{wa})^{2}}{(1-p_{wf})^{4}}.\label{eq:fleiss variance}\\
\sigma_{C}^{2} & = & \sigma_{A}^{2}\frac{1}{(1-p_{wc})^{2}}-2\sigma_{CA}\frac{1-p_{wa}}{(1-p_{wc})^{3}}+\sigma_{C}^{2}\frac{(1-p_{wa})^{2}}{(1-p_{wc})^{4}},\label{eq:cohen variance}\\
\sigma_{BP}^{2} & = & \sigma_{A}^{2}\frac{C^{2}}{(1-C)^{2}},\label{eq:brennan-prediger variance}\\
\sigma_{CF}^{2} & = & (1-p_{wf})^{-2}\left(1,-1,\nu_{CBP}\right)\Sigma\left(1,-1,\nu_{CBP}\right)^{T},\label{eq:cohen-fleiss variance}\\
\sigma_{CBP}^{2} & = & \frac{\sigma_{A}^{2}-2\sigma_{CA}+\sigma_{C}^{2}}{(1-\boldsymbol{1}^{T}W\boldsymbol{1}/C^{2})^{2}}.\label{eq:cohen-brennan-prediger variance}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Proposition 2"
key "Anon2022-ep"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The simple proof for the Cohen–Fleiss coefficient is in the appendix, p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:asymptotic variances"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The asymptotic variance of the Brennan–Prediger coefficient is well-known
 and the easiest to derive.
 The variance of the Cohen–Brennan–Prediger coefficient follows immediately
 from an application of the delta method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a placeholder for 
\begin_inset Formula $F,C,BP,CF,$
\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula $CBP$
\end_inset

, we use an empirical approach that coincides with that of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2021-ht"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in the special case of Fleiss' kappa with nominal weights.
 See the comments following Proposition 1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Anon2022-ep"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Confidence intervals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Anon2022-ep"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 found that the arcsine interval tends to do slightly better than the untransfor
med interval for agreement coefficients with rectangular design.
 For that reason, we will only look at the arcsine interval here.
 Using the delta method, together with the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dx}\arcsin(x)=1/\sqrt{1-x^{2}}$
\end_inset

, we find that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{n}(\arcsin\hat{\nu}_{x}-\arcsin\nu_{x})\stackrel{d}{\to}N(0,(1-\nu_{x}^{2})^{-1}\sigma_{x}^{2}),\label{eq:arcsine interval}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\stackrel{d}{\to}$
\end_inset

 denotes convergence in distribution and 
\begin_inset Formula $\arcsin x$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of the sine function.
 Again, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a placeholder for 
\begin_inset Formula $F,C,BP,CF,$
\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula $CBP$
\end_inset

.
 Define the arcsine interval as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
CI_{x}=\sin\left(\arcsin\hat{\nu}\pm t_{1-\alpha/2}(n-1)(1-\hat{\nu}_{x}^{2})^{-1}\hat{\sigma}_{x}^{2}\right),\label{eq:arcsine CI}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is estimated empirically, as described in the previous subsection, and
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\nu}_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the sample estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{x}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

