\begin_layout Subsection
Coverage of the confidence intervals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the arcsine interval and nominally weighted coefficients.
 The settings of our simulation study follows the settings of the first
 sensitivity analysis closely.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $N=10,000$
\end_inset

 repetitions and the following simulation parameters:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Number of judges
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $2,5,20$
\end_inset

, corresponding to a small, medium, and large selection of judges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Sample sizes
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $n=20,100$
\end_inset

, corresponding to small and large agreement studies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Model.

\series default
 We simulate from the judge skill model used in the sensitivity study (p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "subsec:sensitivity independence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In some cases the simulation yields data frames with only identical values.
 Our confidence interval construction do not cover these instances, so we
 decided to discard these simulations, repeating the simulation until we
 got a data frame with at least two different values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
True distribution centered on the uniform distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the same setup as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:True-distribution-centered-uniform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, where we studied deviations from two assumptions.
 (a), that the true distribution is centered on the uniform distribution,
 (b) that the guessing distributions are equal.
 
\end_layout

