\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:coverage-marginal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 contains the results of the simulation.
 All coefficients, except the Brennan–Prediger coefficient, perform poorly
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is far from the uniform.
 The Cohen–Fleiss coefficient has poor coverage when the true distribution
 is far away from the marginal distribution; likewise for Fleiss' kappa
 and Cohen's kappa.
 The Brennan–Prediger coefficient performs surprisingly well, with far better
 coverage than Cohen's kappa, Fleiss' kappa, and the Cohen–Fleiss coefficient.
 On the other hand, the Cohen–Brennan–Prediger coefficient performs poorly.
 The coverage when 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is far from the uniform or 
\begin_inset Formula $n=100$
\end_inset

 is unacceptably low for all coefficients except the Brennan–Prediger coefficien
t.
 
\end_layout

