\begin_layout Standard
The results are in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:coverage-uniform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The most striking feature is, once again, the poor performance of every
 coefficient except the Brennan–Prediger coefficient.
 The Brennan–Prediger coefficient performs well, with a coverage of approximatel
y 
\begin_inset Formula $0.95$
\end_inset

 in most scenarios when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=20$
\end_inset

.
 What's more, its length is always the smallest.
 Cohen's kappa, Fleiss' kappa, and the Cohen–Fleiss coefficient performs
 decently, except when the marginal distribution is far away from the uniform,
 when their coverage is dismal.
 The Cohen–Brennan–Prediger coefficients performs worse than the others,
 with larger confidence interval lengths and horrible coverage.
 Compared to Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:coverage-marginal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the coverages in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:coverage-uniform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are much worse.
 Even the best-performing Brennan–Prediger coefficient gets as low as 
\begin_inset Formula $0.58$
\end_inset

 at a point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Concluding remarks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the guessing model, a judge either knows – with 
\begin_inset Formula $100\%$
\end_inset

 certainty – the correct classification, or he makes a guess.
 A more realistic model would let knowledge come in degrees.
 A judge could be, say, 
\begin_inset Formula $70\%$
\end_inset

 sure that a patient is X, 
\begin_inset Formula $20\%$
\end_inset

 sure that he is Y, and 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

 spread evenly on the remaining options.
 In epistemology, the 
\emph on
credence function
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pettigrew2019-li"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 quantifies his degree of belief in the different propositions.
 Defining and working with knowledge coefficients in more general 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

credence models
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 might be possible, but identifiability issues looms large.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sensitivity and coverage studies in this paper are limited in scope,
 as they only covers nominal weights and and a small number of parameter
 tweaks.
 Larger simulation study could potentially confirm or disconfirm our recommendat
ion of reporting Cohen's kappa and Fleiss' kappa together with the Brennan–Predi
ger coefficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We reiterate that the agreement coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is justified using a guessing model similar to the first Maxwell's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Maxwell1977-lf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (discussed on p.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "subsec:maxwell"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), but it is not a knowledge coefficient.
 The relationship between the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the knowledge coefficient will be explored in a future paper.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have only discussed a rather peculiar sort of estimation of the knowledge
 coefficient.
 It would, perhaps, be more natural to discuss traditional estimation methods,
 such maximum likelihood estimation, as explored by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Aickin1990-nj"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Klauer1996-jd"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in their submodels of the guessing model.
 In particular, composite maximum likelihood estimation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Varin2011-nv"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 appears to be a good fit to the problem.
 Bayesian estimation could also be a reasonable option.
 If we only care about performance measures such as the mean squared error,
 the Brennan–Prediger coefficient has small bias under many scenarios, and
 its variance is virtually guaranteed to be smaller than the variance of
 a composite maximum likelihood estimator.
 But if we care about inference, even the superior confidence intervals
 for the Brennan–Prediger coefficient have unacceptably poor coverage under
 some circumstances.
 Since constructing approximate confidence intervals for maximum likelihood
 and composite maximum likelihood is routine, going this route will likely
 fix the coverage problem.
\end_layout

